When you call:
Navigator.of(context)
Flutter finds the nearest Navigator above that context in the widget tree.
But sometimes there are multiple Navigators.
rootNavigator: true tells Flutter:
Ignore nested navigators. Use the top-most (root) navigator in the app.


üîé Why Are There Multiple Navigators?
Common situations:
BottomNavigationBar with separate navigation stacks per tab
Nested navigation (e.g., inside a feature module)
showDialog / showModalBottomSheet
ShellRoute in GoRouter
Navigator inside a modal


üî• Example Scenario: Bottom Navigation
Structure:
MaterialApp
   ‚Üì
Root Navigator
   ‚Üì
HomeScreen
   ‚Üì
Tab1 Navigator
   ‚Üì
Tab1 Page
Each tab may have its own Navigator.


‚ùó Problem Without rootNavigator
Suppose you show a dialog inside Tab1:
showDialog(
  context: context,
  builder: (_) => AlertDialog(...),
);
Now you want to dismiss it from somewhere else:
Navigator.of(context).pop();
If context belongs to Tab1‚Äôs nested navigator,
it may try to pop the tab route instead of the dialog.
Unexpected behavior:
Screen pops instead of dialog
Nothing happens
Wrong stack manipulated


‚úÖ Using rootNavigator: true
Navigator.of(context, rootNavigator: true).pop();
Now Flutter:
Looks for the top-most navigator
Pops from the root navigation stack
Ensures dialog is dismissed properly


üß† What Actually Happens Internally
Navigator lookup algorithm:
Without rootNavigator:
Find nearest ancestor Navigator
With rootNavigator: true:
Traverse up to the very top Navigator in the app


üî• When You Typically Need It
1Ô∏è‚É£ Dismissing Dialog From Nested Navigation
If dialog was shown using root navigator but you are inside nested tab context.

2Ô∏è‚É£ When Using BottomNavigationBar with Separate Navigators
Each tab may have:
Navigator(
  key: tabNavigatorKey,
)
If you call pop normally,
it may pop tab stack instead of global overlay.

3Ô∏è‚É£ When You Want Global Navigation
Example:
Force logout
Show global loading dialog
Show app-level error dialog
You want to affect the entire app navigation, not local stack.


‚ùå When You Should NOT Use It
If you‚Äôre intentionally navigating within a tab‚Äôs own stack.
Using rootNavigator in that case:
Breaks tab-level navigation logic
Pops entire app stack unexpectedly

üîé Clean Comparison
Call	What It Pops
Navigator.of(context).pop()	Nearest navigator
Navigator.of(context, rootNavigator: true).pop()	Top-most navigator

üéØ Simple Rule
If you are unsure:
Ask yourself:
Do I want to affect only this local flow or the entire app navigation?
Local flow ‚Üí normal pop
Global overlay/dialog ‚Üí rootNavigator

üß© Real-World Example
If dialog shown like this:
showDialog(
  context: context,
  useRootNavigator: true,
)
Then you should dismiss it using:
Navigator.of(context, rootNavigator: true).pop();
Consistency matters.
